1
00:00:01,415 --> 00:00:11,410
What I wanted to sort of talk about really was this linkage, try and make some linkage anyway, between the meditation we do and ordinary daily life.

2
00:00:14,134 --> 00:00:20,824
And I wanted to approach it in a slightly different way in terms of view of the paths, the different paths of enlightenment.

3
00:00:22,065 --> 00:00:23,288
And

4
00:00:23,739 --> 00:00:35,094
I've sort of, I think we can talk about five different types of ways of looking at the spiritual paths, the religious paths.

5
00:00:35,113 --> 00:00:38,337
The first one I think you're very conversant with, the fundamentalist.

6
00:00:38,838 --> 00:00:43,904
And the next one is a sort of relativist fundamentalist.

7
00:00:45,865 --> 00:00:46,987
Then there's the relativist.

8
00:00:48,450 --> 00:00:50,472
Then there's the relativist universalist.

9
00:00:51,313 --> 00:00:53,054
And then of course there's the universalist.

10
00:00:54,604 --> 00:00:55,326
Need I explain?

11
00:00:58,831 --> 00:01:06,042
So what I mean by the fundamentalist is someone who says, I'm right, everybody else is wrong.

12
00:01:06,581 --> 00:01:08,865
It's a pretty easy universe to live in.

13
00:01:09,626 --> 00:01:10,507
I'm right, everybody else is wrong.

14
00:01:11,530 --> 00:01:13,331
I'm the only one climbing a mountain.

15
00:01:13,552 --> 00:01:16,876
Everybody else is thinking they're climbing a mountain, but actually they are descending a pit.

16
00:01:18,620 --> 00:01:20,042
They're moving towards perdition.

17
00:01:20,683 --> 00:01:23,165
And the world's very simple.

18
00:01:23,186 --> 00:01:24,308
Everybody's got to become like me.

19
00:01:25,992 --> 00:01:28,155
This obviously doesn't have much respect for other traditions.

20
00:01:30,057 --> 00:01:39,629
The relativist fundamentalists, what I mean by that, are people who have a sort of respect for other traditions and accept that they are, in fact, climbing mountains.

21
00:01:40,150 --> 00:01:42,212
But of course, my mountain is higher.

22
00:01:43,674 --> 00:01:47,838
And at some point you will wake up and you realize that I'm up here and you're down there and you'll come over.

23
00:01:48,560 --> 00:01:49,762
That's pretty straightforward too.

24
00:01:52,625 --> 00:01:55,728
The relativist is one who...

25
00:01:56,215 --> 00:02:00,700
says that they're all mountains and you can't distinguish one from the other.

26
00:02:01,540 --> 00:02:04,343
You don't know whether the top of one mountain is the same as the other.

27
00:02:04,683 --> 00:02:08,407
They're completely relative and it doesn't really matter which one you climb.

28
00:02:09,268 --> 00:02:11,570
And that's of course the post-modernist, isn't it?

29
00:02:12,551 --> 00:02:16,536
It's basically a lot of the stuff that's peddled these days.

30
00:02:17,336 --> 00:02:17,917
How can you tell?

31
00:02:18,037 --> 00:02:21,441
It's a case of your take on the truth, your take on reality.

32
00:02:23,842 --> 00:02:25,344
The fourth position

33
00:02:25,763 --> 00:02:44,911
is this relativist universalist who actually perceives that all religions are on the same mountain and that they're all going towards some sort of final resolution and that reading the mystics of these religions, they seem to be saying much the same thing.

34
00:02:46,133 --> 00:02:52,141
But when I say relativist universalist, it's that they still see religions

35
00:02:53,388 --> 00:03:08,376
they still see three separate four or five separate religions going up this path but I think what the universalist sees and this is of course where I am myself

36
00:03:10,414 --> 00:03:18,284
is that there are actually three paths and that they are expressed through a culture in its own way.

37
00:03:18,405 --> 00:03:23,871
And that depending on the culture, you get a leaning to one path rather than the other.

38
00:03:25,894 --> 00:03:32,641
Now, the one religion which has them, I think, at least fairly well delineated in a very clear way is Hinduism.

39
00:03:33,483 --> 00:03:38,574
Hinduism talks about the three yogas, jnana, bhakti and karma.

40
00:03:38,594 --> 00:03:46,313
And that they refer to the path of knowledge, the path of investigation, insight, the path of devotion and the path of action.

41
00:03:48,840 --> 00:03:51,306
But the three, I think what you might call the three...

42
00:03:52,484 --> 00:04:05,419
fully world religions, the three that have actually transcended culture and really spread about the world, Buddhism, Christianity and Islam, you can see here that each one of them has a particular bent.

43
00:04:07,021 --> 00:04:09,025
Buddhism is definitely Gnostic.

44
00:04:09,044 --> 00:04:12,368
Most of it is about some sort of understanding.

45
00:04:12,528 --> 00:04:16,454
It starts always with right understanding.

46
00:04:16,494 --> 00:04:18,896
The Eightfold Path starts with right understanding.

47
00:04:20,345 --> 00:04:23,468
Christianity is very much to do with love, isn't it?

48
00:04:23,569 --> 00:04:30,516
It's coming from a sort of bhakti, a devotional thing, which then expresses itself through compassionate action.

49
00:04:31,557 --> 00:04:36,642
And Islam, just its very word, subservience to the will of God, you see, doing the right thing.

50
00:04:37,403 --> 00:04:39,646
And it's very interesting to see these three leaders.

51
00:04:40,668 --> 00:04:46,233
The Buddha, in himself...

52
00:04:47,564 --> 00:04:50,750
And he's very outside society.

53
00:04:51,593 --> 00:04:52,815
I mean, he's obviously drawn in.

54
00:04:52,875 --> 00:04:56,944
People go to him for advice and stuff, but he's very much separate.

55
00:04:57,425 --> 00:05:04,019
And he's created this little group of monks and nuns which are specific to a specific task.

56
00:05:04,387 --> 00:05:07,833
And lay people, of course, are very much invited in.

57
00:05:08,673 --> 00:05:10,976
But he never gets too involved in lay life.

58
00:05:11,398 --> 00:05:17,346
So, strictly speaking, there's no ceremonies, you know, of marriage, death ceremonies, anything like that at all.

59
00:05:17,386 --> 00:05:18,708
He doesn't take part in any of that.

60
00:05:19,007 --> 00:05:22,132
He leaves all that to the culture around him.

61
00:05:24,276 --> 00:05:29,603
And his drive, ever since he left home, is seemingly this wanting to know.

62
00:05:30,004 --> 00:05:34,630
He just wanted to know whether there was an end to this suffering or not, or this dissatisfaction.

63
00:05:35,572 --> 00:05:36,872
So that's the driving force.

64
00:05:36,932 --> 00:05:38,855
It's the driving force of a scientist, isn't it?

65
00:05:40,718 --> 00:05:41,439
Wanting to know.

66
00:05:41,478 --> 00:05:49,168
The devotional person is much more concerned with how to relate, isn't it?

67
00:05:49,208 --> 00:05:51,089
How to relate from a heart base.

68
00:05:52,451 --> 00:05:56,637
Much more to do with an emotional heart relationship.

69
00:05:57,257 --> 00:06:06,670
And Christianity developed these enormous meditations and contemplations of Jesus Christ, through Jesus Christ.

70
00:06:07,451 --> 00:06:13,497
Now, if you read the Mystics, interestingly enough, this meditation on Jesus is only half the way.

71
00:06:13,557 --> 00:06:22,309
Once you've developed this pure loving, this pure heart which is full of love, if you read people like, say, John of the Cross, then you have to leave all that.

72
00:06:22,529 --> 00:06:23,630
You have to leave all that completely.

73
00:06:23,850 --> 00:06:26,134
And he keeps going on about nothingness, nothingness.

74
00:06:26,485 --> 00:06:53,117
so the whole business of this purification is to do with a. getting rid of all that is nasty within us which is equally the same with the Buddhist path and then developing this heart of love which is purified and laser beamed and all that sort of stuff and then letting go of that until you leave go of anything which is phenomenal and Christian mystics often talk about things like nothingness

75
00:06:53,586 --> 00:06:54,389
The void.

76
00:06:56,375 --> 00:06:57,879
See?

77
00:06:57,899 --> 00:07:01,588
Jesus Christ, of course, was very much, he was sort of half way, wasn't he?

78
00:07:01,749 --> 00:07:08,608
I mean, he was in society, but he wasn't particularly involved in it, but he definitely wanted to change it.

79
00:07:09,112 --> 00:07:29,247
See, unlike the Buddha, he definitely wanted to change things in that society and bring about some sort of revolution in that, especially with the way that religion was being taught, etc., through rules and regulations, and to bring in this whole idea of something which was beyond religion.

80
00:07:29,581 --> 00:07:34,225
to my mind anyway, a personal God, believe it or not.

81
00:07:34,305 --> 00:07:35,867
But that's just my own little view on things.

82
00:07:36,408 --> 00:07:45,776
It was only later that when Christianity left Judaism and came into the Roman Empire that it began to be reinterpreted by way of those people.

83
00:07:46,437 --> 00:07:49,740
And remember that the Roman Empire at that time was polytheistic.

84
00:07:50,261 --> 00:07:54,545
So the next movement from believing that there are many gods is to believe in one personal God.

85
00:07:54,584 --> 00:07:55,386
That's your shift.

86
00:07:55,771 --> 00:08:24,545
and then only then do you shift to a higher level where there is an impersonal God so you see that in Hinduism from Brahma, Shiva and then they go on to Brahman, the neutral you can see that shift of consciousness so you see that Jesus is very much involved and he lives in society he doesn't go out into the I mean he has little times off in the desert but basically he lives right there he moves from house to house living with ordinary people

87
00:08:29,723 --> 00:08:33,089
And his teaching, of course, is basically about love, isn't it?

88
00:08:33,328 --> 00:08:34,171
About love.

89
00:08:35,332 --> 00:08:42,846
Now, when you get to Muhammad, Muhammad was rather interesting because he obviously had a very deep spiritual insight, but he didn't like monasteries.

90
00:08:42,865 --> 00:08:45,471
He didn't like it at all.

91
00:08:45,940 --> 00:08:48,062
He was married and lived an ordinary life.

92
00:08:48,602 --> 00:08:55,690
So what he had to do, in a sort of peculiar way, was to create a monastery, inverted commas, around him.

93
00:08:56,190 --> 00:09:07,421
So instead of creating a little group of people who would be directly involved in trying to become enlightened, or whatever word you want to use, he has to involve everybody.

94
00:09:08,601 --> 00:09:13,466
Well, in doing that, of course, you've got to deal with all sorts of characters, and hence the rules have to be

95
00:09:13,868 --> 00:09:16,571
a little bit more strict, so you get this growth of the Sharia.

96
00:09:18,293 --> 00:09:22,596
But his thing was the will of God, you see, action, the will of God.

97
00:09:23,337 --> 00:09:34,750
And the jihad was, in its most corrupt form, of course, is about the spread of Islam, but in its most purest form, he himself said the inner jihad is more important than the outer one.

98
00:09:35,071 --> 00:09:42,558
So this inner jihad, of course, was to struggle with the bad conditionings or whatever that's inside us, to purify ourselves.

99
00:09:44,075 --> 00:09:53,370
And again, if you read Sufi literature, you know, they also talk about getting into this final state of nothingness.

100
00:09:54,532 --> 00:09:55,933
The word just slips my mind now.

101
00:09:56,414 --> 00:09:56,995
Does anybody know it?

102
00:10:01,844 --> 00:10:01,903
No?

103
00:10:01,923 --> 00:10:02,164
Sorry?

104
00:10:03,527 --> 00:10:05,990
No, no, I was thinking of the Sufi word for it.

105
00:10:07,472 --> 00:10:07,974
Faniya.

106
00:10:08,335 --> 00:10:09,035
Faniya.

107
00:10:09,943 --> 00:10:31,563
and what they mean by that is you know if you read the literature seems to be saying the same thing as what the Buddha is saying so if we just for a moment take this universalist position that there are three paths the path of understanding the path of mind the path of the heart and the path of action the body you see

108
00:10:32,184 --> 00:10:40,277
and we turn to the Eightfold Noble Path, then we can see that, in a sense, it is included in that.

109
00:10:41,057 --> 00:10:44,102
So, what we have, first of all, is right understanding.

110
00:10:45,184 --> 00:10:48,929
And what the Buddha means by that is that we have to see things correctly.

111
00:10:49,591 --> 00:10:53,336
And we have to get beyond the delusion that ego puts us into.

112
00:10:53,977 --> 00:10:57,884
Now, the fundamental delusion of ego is to believe that this is what we are.

113
00:10:58,124 --> 00:10:59,725
You know, when you look in the mirror, this is me.

114
00:11:00,386 --> 00:11:00,807
Yeah?

115
00:11:00,940 --> 00:11:03,243
When you've got a headache, I'm suffering.

116
00:11:03,823 --> 00:11:05,706
When you feel happy, it's me that's happy.

117
00:11:06,187 --> 00:11:08,971
So everything we experience, we experience as me.

118
00:11:10,173 --> 00:11:13,418
Now what he's saying is that this is a delusion.

119
00:11:15,240 --> 00:11:18,446
So he asks us to, as it were, deconstruct the event.

120
00:11:19,206 --> 00:11:24,855
Through the meditation you begin to see that what we thought was whole and entire is just made up of parts.

121
00:11:25,274 --> 00:11:26,855
Even the simple act of eating.

122
00:11:27,236 --> 00:11:28,418
There's many things going on.

123
00:11:28,719 --> 00:11:30,902
There's taste at the sense base.

124
00:11:30,942 --> 00:11:33,605
There's a heart response of enjoyment.

125
00:11:34,206 --> 00:11:35,990
And there's this consciousness that knows.

126
00:11:36,350 --> 00:11:40,495
There's lots of little bits and pieces that go into making up one simple event.

127
00:11:42,639 --> 00:11:44,982
He asks us to see that nothing is permanent.

128
00:11:46,745 --> 00:11:49,208
The ego likes to be permanent, doesn't it?

129
00:11:49,428 --> 00:11:51,312
You want to be here forever.

130
00:11:51,392 --> 00:11:51,552
Forever.

131
00:11:52,291 --> 00:11:53,452
We don't want to change.

132
00:11:54,094 --> 00:11:55,817
And we don't see that change.

133
00:11:55,836 --> 00:12:00,784
We might see it in the leaves outside and in people dying and all that, but we don't particularly see it in ourselves.

134
00:12:01,645 --> 00:12:07,535
If we really saw it in ourselves, then we wouldn't be so attached to these emotions, to these thoughts.

135
00:12:07,696 --> 00:12:10,299
We'd actually see them as just passing phenomena.

136
00:12:16,759 --> 00:12:21,525
And at Fundament, in terms of our psychology, we're very much committed to this life form.

137
00:12:22,046 --> 00:12:25,210
We think we can be really happy here if we just get it right.

138
00:12:25,571 --> 00:12:29,716
You know, the right job, the right partner, the right... And then I'll be happy.

139
00:12:30,316 --> 00:12:31,437
You can draw a line, finally.

140
00:12:31,937 --> 00:12:32,438
See?

141
00:12:32,458 --> 00:12:41,649
So that investment in our lives as a place where we're going to find happiness, from the Buddhist point of view, is a profound illusion because everything's arising and passing away.

142
00:12:41,669 --> 00:12:44,033
And secondly...

143
00:12:44,535 --> 00:12:49,102
There's a presumption there of it being me, of an identity, something that you can control.

144
00:12:49,163 --> 00:12:52,287
That's the definition of me, isn't it?

145
00:12:52,307 --> 00:12:53,168
I can control it.

146
00:12:55,471 --> 00:13:03,844
And the fact of the matter is that even when we are delightfully happy with something, there's a sort of inbuilt obsolescence to pleasure.

147
00:13:04,125 --> 00:13:06,969
I mean, the same chocolate won't do, will it?

148
00:13:08,831 --> 00:13:10,053
You've got to go out and buy something else.

149
00:13:12,096 --> 00:13:13,698
Variety is the spice of life.

150
00:13:17,559 --> 00:13:22,548
So now, if we take that, you see, as a right understanding, how does it affect the heart?

151
00:13:22,567 --> 00:13:24,571
You see, so that's your next step, right attitude.

152
00:13:24,850 --> 00:13:26,514
So you drop down into right attitude.

153
00:13:26,813 --> 00:13:30,620
From right understanding, we develop right attitude.

154
00:13:31,120 --> 00:13:40,294
Right attitude is normally described as moving from hatred to love, cruelty to compassion, stinginess or selfishness to generosity.

155
00:13:40,816 --> 00:13:43,720
But in fact, it's the movement of all vice to virtue.

156
00:13:46,365 --> 00:13:57,544
And that is a development in our attitude, in other words, the way we feel about things, the way we look at things, and that immediately affects our emotional life.

157
00:13:59,448 --> 00:14:09,605
So in the Buddhist way of doing things, you move from right understanding, so it affects your attitude, and then the next flows, right speech, right action, right livelihood.

158
00:14:10,666 --> 00:14:19,556
So if we go into a situation with the right understanding and the right attitude, then our speech will be truthful, it will be kind, it will be gentle, and so on.

159
00:14:19,635 --> 00:14:24,640
We won't fall into the error of telling whoppers and all that sort of stuff.

160
00:14:27,264 --> 00:14:30,827
Coarse language, shouting at each other.

161
00:14:30,847 --> 00:14:38,817
And when we're in an action of any sort, then we'll do it with that mindfulness, with that carefulness.

162
00:14:39,100 --> 00:14:43,025
And finally, our livelihood will be careful what we do with most of our lives.

163
00:14:43,365 --> 00:14:45,950
Because what we do has an effect on our personality, doesn't it?

164
00:14:46,971 --> 00:14:50,657
See?

165
00:14:50,677 --> 00:14:53,981
I mean, supposing now you decided to join a drug gang.

166
00:14:54,923 --> 00:14:59,370
It would be different, wouldn't it?

167
00:14:59,389 --> 00:15:01,192
And you'd have to develop different qualities.

168
00:15:03,534 --> 00:15:06,488
So what you do is very material.

169
00:15:06,808 --> 00:15:10,565
Now, you can see the feedback here, can't you?

170
00:15:10,986 --> 00:15:11,791
See, there's a loop.

171
00:15:12,172 --> 00:15:13,477
So what we do...

172
00:15:13,980 --> 00:15:19,288
What we say and how we act feeds back to reinforce that attitude.

173
00:15:19,707 --> 00:15:23,854
There's a feedback because the world responds to us when we're good in some way.

174
00:15:24,414 --> 00:15:26,197
So there's a feedback which reinforces it.

175
00:15:26,596 --> 00:15:33,645
This attitude then reinforces or puts a stamp of approval on the way we've seen things.

176
00:15:34,147 --> 00:15:37,792
And therefore there's more effort to see things even more clearly.

177
00:15:38,712 --> 00:15:40,274
So there's a round, isn't there, there?

178
00:15:41,892 --> 00:15:53,043
And that fundament beneath all that, that is this practice of meditation, which is basically to do with getting that right, the right understanding, the right attitude, and the right action, speech, and livelihood.

179
00:15:53,945 --> 00:15:54,926
That's what it's supporting.

180
00:15:55,547 --> 00:16:11,764
So what the Buddha's saying is that we have to take some sort of position within ourselves so that we can see very clearly what's going on, where we're making mistakes, where we're being unskillful, and where we're being skillful, where we're actually doing what is correct, you see.

181
00:16:14,004 --> 00:16:33,509
So our meditation is primarily concerned with accessing a post of observation in ourselves, in the sitting posture, where we can see the mind and the heart unfolding, just offering its goods to us, sometimes turbulence, sometimes loveliness.

182
00:16:34,270 --> 00:16:40,259
And then somehow we have to learn how to maintain that mindfulness when we go from the sitting posture into ordinary daily life.

183
00:16:43,442 --> 00:16:43,523
Hmm?

184
00:16:45,966 --> 00:16:58,620
And one of the important things to remember is that when you move into daily life, you see, to maintain that mindfulness, you have to be careful not to be hijacked by emotions, sort of snowballed by them.

185
00:16:59,200 --> 00:17:12,614
So there has to be this constant effort to stop whatever you're doing, to stop, recollect what you've done, catch the little bit of silence, the centeredness, and then intend and do the next thing.

186
00:17:13,055 --> 00:17:15,416
And in this way you create these breaks, you see.

187
00:17:15,868 --> 00:17:21,194
Even answering a telephone, you see, the normal action is to sort of launch yourself at it.

188
00:17:22,256 --> 00:17:24,037
But I mean, most people wait for three rings.

189
00:17:24,958 --> 00:17:26,740
I'm very impatient if they wait for three rings.

190
00:17:27,421 --> 00:17:34,208
So when you hear the bell, you see, if you're in an office or something, you have to spend a moment just recognising what you're doing.

191
00:17:34,288 --> 00:17:36,691
It's a moment of acknowledgement, of recollection.

192
00:17:38,271 --> 00:17:44,778
Then you turn to the phone, you see, and in that moment there's a little silence and you're ready to receive the phone call.

193
00:17:45,400 --> 00:17:49,846
If you try to do two things at once, then this motor starts up.

194
00:17:52,431 --> 00:17:57,538
So it's these little techniques that bring this mindfulness to daily life, you see.

195
00:17:58,079 --> 00:18:01,184
The mindfulness is coming from right understanding.

196
00:18:01,685 --> 00:18:05,131
The right understanding sees a situation and what it needs.

197
00:18:05,151 --> 00:18:07,595
It also sees what it needs from the heart point of view.

198
00:18:07,915 --> 00:18:12,623
The right attitude arises within a given situation and the right action is taken.

199
00:18:13,108 --> 00:18:16,377
And the whole thing begins to, as it were, work for us.

200
00:18:16,438 --> 00:18:18,544
It's a sort of new conditioning.

201
00:18:24,901 --> 00:18:28,671
Now because there's this loop, you can see you can start from any vantage point.

202
00:18:29,308 --> 00:18:47,992
generally speaking in this sort of school you always start from the meditation but you could equally start by just developing right relationships with people and concentrating on that and that would loop into the way you understand how things are and how you should do things properly

203
00:18:49,558 --> 00:18:54,906
If you concentrate on doing, on good works, and it can be anything, remember.

204
00:18:54,926 --> 00:18:58,432
It doesn't have to be, you know, you don't have to go and look after lepers or something.

205
00:18:58,833 --> 00:19:04,681
I mean, you can just carry bins about, you know, but it's the way we do things with this carefulness and attention, you see.

206
00:19:05,301 --> 00:19:10,048
Even that has its effect upon the way we see things and the way we feel about things.

207
00:19:12,992 --> 00:19:14,976
So there are three starting points.

208
00:19:15,529 --> 00:19:24,508
This right understanding, right attitude, and right action, speech, and livelihood, which include just this right action, this way of doing.

209
00:19:24,567 --> 00:19:32,785
So when lay people say to me, well, it's all right for a monk, you're not doing anything all day.

210
00:19:34,930 --> 00:19:36,593
I don't.

211
00:19:36,978 --> 00:19:38,961
You've got all this time in your life.

212
00:19:39,242 --> 00:19:40,565
But what about us, you see?

213
00:19:41,046 --> 00:19:46,297
Well, that's a wrong understanding to my point of view because there's too much of an accent on the sitting meditation.

214
00:19:47,259 --> 00:19:53,112
There's too much of an accent thinking that you've got to do these vast long sits in order to get enlightened.

215
00:19:53,412 --> 00:19:58,142
But actually, if you get your daily life right, you'll see that the whole thing begins to work for you.

216
00:19:58,477 --> 00:20:02,023
Because it's coming from right livelihood, right action, right speech.

217
00:20:02,565 --> 00:20:07,373
As soon as you do something good, you've got to feel there's got to be a training in the heart.

218
00:20:07,394 --> 00:20:08,756
There's got to be a right understanding.

219
00:20:12,663 --> 00:20:16,269
So that's why in the scriptures, a cobbler becomes fully enlightened.

220
00:20:16,990 --> 00:20:17,712
Cobbling his shoes.

221
00:20:18,513 --> 00:20:20,096
Well, a cobbler can do it.

222
00:20:21,410 --> 00:20:32,482
And a woman has this great insight, I think it's first path and fruit, just caring for the bread in the oven, just the crackling, you see, seeing the anicca, the transiency.

223
00:20:50,704 --> 00:20:51,486
So take heart.

224
00:20:52,768 --> 00:20:53,669
It's only around the corner.

225
00:20:56,432 --> 00:20:57,212
Keep struggling with it.

226
00:21:06,525 --> 00:21:11,931
So let me just say something just quickly about daily life.

227
00:21:14,615 --> 00:21:20,442
I think this business of stopping and starting

228
00:21:21,636 --> 00:21:36,612
Really cutting the day up into pieces where you recollect what you're doing and stopping, you see, just allows any emotional turbulence which you've accumulated through some sort of conversation or somebody says something nasty to you, just allows it to die down.

229
00:21:37,413 --> 00:21:47,022
And then, just in that little moment, you can collect yourself and then go into the next moment with that sort of more liberated mind.

230
00:21:47,663 --> 00:21:49,685
A mind which is not caught up in something.

231
00:21:50,070 --> 00:21:51,251
You can do it any time.

232
00:21:51,313 --> 00:21:54,236
You can do it walking up the stairs, opening and closing a door.

233
00:21:54,517 --> 00:21:58,300
So you're in one room and somebody's something and you're irritated, you see.

234
00:21:58,561 --> 00:22:01,045
Well, normally you'd walk into the next room and take it with you.

235
00:22:01,806 --> 00:22:03,166
And whoever's in there gets it as well.

236
00:22:04,169 --> 00:22:12,298
But if you just stop for a moment, just close the door and just let it all die down, you see, and wait, just wait for it to pass, then you don't carry it, you see.

237
00:22:15,281 --> 00:22:19,807
There's this business, you know, of bringing a bit of ceremony back into our lives.

238
00:22:20,345 --> 00:22:21,707
You know, like when we...

239
00:22:22,648 --> 00:22:32,765
I mean, now, you know, so many people sort of just grab something out of the fridge, stick it on a plate, turn the TV on and sit there munching and grunching and watching.

240
00:22:32,785 --> 00:22:36,049
And it's like life becomes more coarse.

241
00:22:36,810 --> 00:22:38,354
There's a certain coarseness to it.

242
00:22:39,655 --> 00:22:40,917
You know, these...

243
00:22:43,700 --> 00:22:49,867
The idea of ceremony is it's a sort of help to your concentration.

244
00:22:49,928 --> 00:22:52,471
It's a sort of help to the whole feeling of something.

245
00:22:52,711 --> 00:23:00,082
So we all know what it's like when you prepare a meal well and you set a table out well and you sit there in front of it.

246
00:23:00,702 --> 00:23:03,125
And, you know, there's a certain ceremony to it.

247
00:23:03,645 --> 00:23:07,855
Instead of... You say, I want a cup of tea.

248
00:23:07,996 --> 00:23:14,230
So you go in there and you bang the kettle about and you stick it under the tap and plug it in and bang the teapot on you.

249
00:23:15,933 --> 00:23:19,142
Slap the kettle, stick it back and you wonder whether you've had a tea or not.

250
00:23:19,182 --> 00:23:19,863
You know what I mean?

251
00:23:19,883 --> 00:23:20,625
So it's a case...

252
00:23:21,112 --> 00:23:29,559
Whereas if it's a moment of mindfulness, then just that way of doing it mindfully immediately brings about a certain way of doing things.

253
00:23:29,861 --> 00:23:31,301
See, a certain ceremony.

254
00:23:33,023 --> 00:23:33,924
Taking our time.

255
00:23:35,125 --> 00:23:36,527
Actually tasting the tea.

256
00:23:40,151 --> 00:23:41,471
Even tying your shoelaces.

257
00:23:42,032 --> 00:23:43,153
See, with delicacy.

258
00:23:49,519 --> 00:23:49,599
Yes.

259
00:23:49,866 --> 00:23:59,859
Well, it's just there's always the next thing to be done.

260
00:24:00,717 --> 00:24:02,500
So it's you intend that.

261
00:24:02,539 --> 00:24:10,090
You make it actually a very conscious, self-conscious, a very conscious decision.

262
00:24:10,632 --> 00:24:14,076
See, often we have about four to five intentions in our mind.

263
00:24:14,396 --> 00:24:15,439
That's why we're rushing about.

264
00:24:15,459 --> 00:24:17,000
We're trying to do ten things at once.

265
00:24:17,981 --> 00:24:19,443
And you just get jumbled over.

266
00:24:19,545 --> 00:24:20,926
You just trip over yourself.

267
00:24:21,386 --> 00:24:27,036
Whereas if you just stop and you prioritise and you make your intention for the next thing, then there's a clarity.

268
00:24:27,476 --> 00:24:30,099
Because you can't do, normally you can't do more than that.

269
00:24:30,416 --> 00:24:32,219
one thing at a time.

270
00:24:32,278 --> 00:24:35,022
When you finish that, you stop, you recollect what you've done, you start.

271
00:24:35,363 --> 00:24:40,628
So you keep regaining that ground of peaceful existence, of calmness, quietness.

272
00:24:42,332 --> 00:24:51,502
And I know that's difficult in work situations which can be stressful and whatnot.

273
00:24:51,843 --> 00:24:59,192
The other, I think, very important insight is to really, really grasp the fact that nobody makes you angry.

274
00:25:01,011 --> 00:25:02,113
Nobody upsets you.

275
00:25:06,198 --> 00:25:07,220
Nobody makes you happy.

276
00:25:11,925 --> 00:25:16,892
I wonder if you've really, really grasped that because when you do, it's an awesome liberation.

277
00:25:18,012 --> 00:25:19,295
You can stop blaming people.

278
00:25:21,637 --> 00:25:26,022
You can actually find the source of the problem within yourself.

279
00:25:27,286 --> 00:25:37,980
You can correct the whole of your life overnight once you've actually really, really, truly grasped that nobody can affect your heart directly.

280
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:44,650
It's always our conditioned response to a given situation or a given person.

281
00:25:45,131 --> 00:25:45,490
Always.

282
00:25:49,616 --> 00:25:51,318
You're looking at me as though you don't believe me.

283
00:25:54,724 --> 00:25:59,212
How many of you would say, I'd actually grasped that.

284
00:26:01,057 --> 00:26:02,077
You'd actually seen it, yeah.

285
00:26:02,839 --> 00:26:03,780
It's very liberating, isn't it?

286
00:26:04,722 --> 00:26:05,944
Because now you stop blaming people.

287
00:26:06,826 --> 00:26:09,070
And you can just take control of your own life.

288
00:26:10,173 --> 00:26:15,061
But that still doesn't mean that you'll stop reacting in that way because of the conditioning.

289
00:26:16,003 --> 00:26:17,646
So you have to guard your heart.

290
00:26:18,167 --> 00:26:27,384
You have to be quick to put a guard, as it were, in front of your heart so that it doesn't bounce off this incoming stimulus.

291
00:26:28,026 --> 00:26:31,633
So an obvious situation is when somebody is angry with us.

292
00:26:32,103 --> 00:26:36,127
So the anger comes, we can feel it, you know, we feel it, we can see it, the person's angry with us.

293
00:26:36,268 --> 00:26:46,619
So our normal reaction is either to combat it, to come at it with anger, or to shrivel, you know, to sort of wither, you see, because you're afraid of it.

294
00:26:47,701 --> 00:26:51,826
Now you have to guide yourself against that sort of connection.

295
00:26:52,246 --> 00:26:53,907
So how are you going to do it, you see?

296
00:26:55,069 --> 00:26:58,093
Well, mindfulness, of course, to be mindful of it is the first step.

297
00:26:58,593 --> 00:27:04,979
Most times we just slip into the old habit of either getting into the argument or allowing that person to ride over us.

298
00:27:06,461 --> 00:27:15,689
So the first thing is the mindfulness, but then there has to be this sort of moment of just inward glancing, where you actually contact the way you're feeling.

299
00:27:17,871 --> 00:27:21,275
And then, as it were, you've got to put your hand over it.

300
00:27:21,994 --> 00:27:23,777
You've got to sort of quieten it, you see.

301
00:27:24,144 --> 00:27:33,980
And when you look up, you see, at the person, or when you re-contact the person, you have to be very careful that you only deal with the problem, not with the person.

302
00:27:35,824 --> 00:27:43,977
Now this means that the person now who is angry with you has to answer the problem and not your personal reaction.

303
00:27:45,323 --> 00:27:51,648
It's sort of an easy thing to do when you try it.

304
00:27:52,269 --> 00:28:02,059
So what the person's getting from you is that their anger, whatever it is they're trying to lay on you, isn't having an effect.

305
00:28:02,601 --> 00:28:05,864
And they feel that in your voice, which is steady, assertive.

306
00:28:05,884 --> 00:28:07,005
So what's the problem?

307
00:28:07,445 --> 00:28:09,086
So you actually discuss the problem.

308
00:28:09,688 --> 00:28:13,811
And that often takes all that stuff out of the situation.

309
00:28:14,634 --> 00:28:19,345
Now, in this sense, you see, we're taught always to offer loving kindness and all that.

310
00:28:19,765 --> 00:28:24,474
But when the heart's responding in that sort of way, it's good enough just to offer no harm.

311
00:28:26,338 --> 00:28:30,667
You don't have to gush with love every time somebody comes at you with a knife.

312
00:28:32,270 --> 00:28:35,277
No harm is a decent position to take, you see.

313
00:28:39,391 --> 00:28:41,737
You can get pretty skillful at that.

314
00:28:42,357 --> 00:28:48,913
I myself have used this business of, I think he's, yeah, you see this posture of the Buddha here.

315
00:28:49,174 --> 00:28:51,641
So that's called the abhaya posture, the fearless posture.

316
00:28:52,102 --> 00:28:57,213
It's meant to come from a time when the dastardly David Arthur set a mad elephant on him.

317
00:28:57,582 --> 00:29:04,816
And as the elephant came towards him, roaring down towards him, you see, he held his hand up, you see, and offered him loving kindness.

318
00:29:05,135 --> 00:29:10,326
The elephant collapsed into a state of adoration by the time he got close to the Buddha, you see.

319
00:29:10,465 --> 00:29:13,612
It's a lovely story, isn't it?

320
00:29:13,632 --> 00:29:16,857
So what he was doing, you see, this hand, you see, was fearless.

321
00:29:18,401 --> 00:29:20,484
But from the heart, he was offering loving kindness.

322
00:29:21,258 --> 00:29:26,585
So I find for myself that's a very potent sort of way of just to image this hand.

323
00:29:27,045 --> 00:29:28,467
It's the Buddha hand.

324
00:29:28,968 --> 00:29:30,410
My own hand is here, you see.

325
00:29:30,809 --> 00:29:35,096
So it's a case of allowing this stuff to come at me, but it doesn't get beyond this hand.

326
00:29:35,195 --> 00:29:37,238
It stays there on the outside.

327
00:29:38,619 --> 00:29:47,191
And from behind this hand, at least I can offer an attitude of no harm, or of at least wanting to know what the problem is, not getting involved in personality.

328
00:29:48,653 --> 00:29:48,732
Hmm?

329
00:30:01,488 --> 00:30:10,096
There's a case where, I think I might have mentioned it before, where the Buddha turns up at a house and this Brahmin has nothing but insults for him.

330
00:30:10,115 --> 00:30:11,998
You know, useless and all that sort of stuff.

331
00:30:12,018 --> 00:30:14,461
What people normally say about me.

332
00:30:15,682 --> 00:30:20,807
And he listens patiently, you see.

333
00:30:20,826 --> 00:30:21,386
He just takes it.

334
00:30:21,768 --> 00:30:26,471
And then he simply asks the man, if somebody offers you a present, do you really have to accept it?

335
00:30:26,833 --> 00:30:28,213
He says, no, you don't have to.

336
00:30:28,233 --> 00:30:31,376
He says, well, everything you offered me, I offer back to you, you see.

337
00:30:31,356 --> 00:30:38,051
So when people are offering you their stuff, you don't have to accept it.

338
00:30:38,092 --> 00:30:39,596
That's their stuff.

339
00:30:43,022 --> 00:30:45,409
You want to take somebody else's suffering off, haven't you got enough of your own?

340
00:30:47,834 --> 00:30:48,615
Leave it with them.

341
00:30:48,936 --> 00:30:49,939
Leave it with them, you see.

342
00:30:50,205 --> 00:31:01,980
And you can do that by taking this objective stance, by seeing the problem, you see, not getting involved in the emotional thing, being aware of what's happening inside us and just being still, you see.

343
00:31:03,843 --> 00:31:07,688
So this is a moment when that consciousness is both outside and inside.

344
00:31:07,708 --> 00:31:10,250
So you remember we have to develop these three positions.

345
00:31:10,612 --> 00:31:16,398
Sometimes we're aware of the inside, sometimes the outside, sometimes both the inside and the outside.

346
00:31:18,573 --> 00:31:24,137
So it's to find that steadiness, you see, and that's really the purpose of the morning meditation.

347
00:31:24,419 --> 00:31:31,105
The morning meditation is a time when we re-establish, recognize where we ought to be for the rest of the day.

348
00:31:31,144 --> 00:31:37,751
So if you miss that, in a sense, you've missed clicking into that frame of, into that level of consciousness.

349
00:31:38,512 --> 00:31:41,434
So then you stay with it and you keep bringing yourself back to that.

350
00:31:42,355 --> 00:31:48,241
See, as many times as you can during the day, you just bring yourself back to that, just to that silence, just to that stillness.

351
00:31:49,993 --> 00:31:50,595
Then you move.

352
00:31:53,159 --> 00:31:59,128
Then when you get to in the evening, you see, the evening meditation is about letting go of all the accumulations.

353
00:31:59,730 --> 00:32:04,778
So it may be that you've developed little irritations and little sadnesses and who knows what, you see.

354
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:09,125
So you have to sit with it and wait till it goes out, you see.

355
00:32:11,347 --> 00:32:14,854
See, just now I got an email, see, a very old friend of mine who's just died.

356
00:32:15,221 --> 00:32:15,823
And it's funny.

357
00:32:16,143 --> 00:32:17,404
You read it and it hits you.

358
00:32:18,106 --> 00:32:18,646
You can feel it.

359
00:32:19,268 --> 00:32:20,430
You know, an old friend died.

360
00:32:20,589 --> 00:32:21,311
That's how you feel.

361
00:32:21,731 --> 00:32:22,553
You feel the sadness.

362
00:32:23,434 --> 00:32:26,480
So I'm going to have to sit with that.

363
00:32:27,902 --> 00:32:32,229
Then it'll go and I'll be happy again.

364
00:32:32,249 --> 00:32:35,834
See, these things come at us and we have to feel them and then you sit with it.

365
00:32:35,973 --> 00:32:37,236
You see, you don't do anything about it.

366
00:32:37,376 --> 00:32:40,842
You just let the heart do what it wants and then it passes away.

367
00:32:46,626 --> 00:33:05,710
The other thing which is important, you know, in terms of the spiritual life is to really find, this is part of the Eightfold Path of right effort, is really, you know, begin to tackle some part of the personality which is unskillful and really work with it.

368
00:33:06,631 --> 00:33:15,402
And what happens is, if you deal with one part of the personality which is unskillful, whatever it is, you know, it shades all the way through, it shades all the way through.

369
00:33:16,478 --> 00:33:23,068
So for instance, since we've talked about anger and all that, if you are very quick angered, you really work with it.

370
00:33:25,332 --> 00:33:33,684
Which means that you have to sit with it, you don't respond to the anger, you keep reminding yourself that any time you walk into a situation this is the way you're going to behave.

371
00:33:34,366 --> 00:33:37,191
And of course that will feed right the way through the personality.

372
00:33:38,472 --> 00:33:40,916
Remember everything is this interconnected business.

373
00:33:42,667 --> 00:33:45,810
And the other thing to do is to choose a virtue.

374
00:33:46,311 --> 00:33:50,316
You don't have to choose it for a very long time, just for the period of time which you want to develop.

375
00:33:52,377 --> 00:33:54,140
And actually develop that virtue.

376
00:33:55,902 --> 00:34:01,227
Some people, for instance, find it very difficult to forgive.

377
00:34:01,988 --> 00:34:02,808
They hold grudges.

378
00:34:03,209 --> 00:34:03,910
So work on it.

379
00:34:04,590 --> 00:34:07,634
Every time somebody says, I forgive you, just keep saying it.

380
00:34:09,416 --> 00:34:11,577
Don't actually indulge.

381
00:34:12,030 --> 00:34:20,876
And then eventually there comes this easy forgiveness, just easily letting go of little insults and little daggers that people stick in us.

382
00:34:31,690 --> 00:34:34,813
So this is the last time I'll probably be seeing you in this way.

383
00:34:35,094 --> 00:34:46,150
So may I wish you a very fruitful practice and that you be enlightened by the end of the week even.

384
00:34:46,170 --> 00:35:00,010
I give you a little blessing.

